The use of stable isotope analysis in food-web ecology and trophic interactions is widespread in ecological studies and is increasingly used for aquaculture and diet investigations on marine organisms. To determine the diet of an animal, various stable isotope mixing models (e.g., MixSIAR, simmr, Fruits) can be used to estimate the proportion of consumer diet from a selection of dietary sources (

; 

; 

). Due to isotopic fractionation, stable isotope delta values change as organisms sit further up or down the trophic cascade. To assess this change, Trophic Discrimination Factors (TDF, denoted by ∆) are used, which are defined as the difference in isotopic values between food source and consumer. Here, we describe species-specific TDFs which can be used to assess the diet of a spiny lobster, the southern rock lobster 

Jasus edwardsii
(
Hutton, 1875
)

.

Mixing models require a TDF to adequately account for changes in uptake of carbon and nitrogen through the food chain. TDFs can vary significantly and therefore mixing models require a TDF to be specific for each tissue 
type
, species, and isotope (e.g., ∆13C and ∆15N). TDFs for a particular species may be obtained from the literature, but ideally are experimentally determined with controlled captive feeding trials. Approximated TDFs produced from averages across multiple taxa can be used if species-specific TDFs are not available in the literature: 0.4‰ for ∆13C and 3.4‰ for ∆15N (

). The use of non-species-specific TDFs will increase uncertainty in the estimation of consumer diet using mixing models (

), and therefore researchers have been urged to use experimentally derived TDFs for mixing models (e.g., 

; Martínez del 

; 

); 

).

To obtain diet information of a consumer by stable isotope analysis, a tissue sample is required from the consumer and from each of the potential diet sources. Muscle tissue is commonly used for analysis because muscle generally reflects the long-term isotope signature and thus reflects longer term diet of the animal and is less prone to short-term changes in diet (

), unlike, for example, hair or shell tissue. In many cases, the required tissue involves lethal sampling of the individual (

). Non-lethal sampling options for crustaceans, such as carapace, leg, antenna, and faeces samples, however, have been proven to be promising alternatives to muscle tissue, due to high isotopic correlations between tissues in some species (

; 

; 

). Non-lethal sampling provides a useful alternative in situations investigating protected populations or long-term, repetitive-sampling experiments. Removing a single leg rather than a more invasive or whole-animal sample, it provides the opportunity to sample industry caught crustaceans destined for market without compromising sale value, which could allow for large sample sizes.

Stable isotope measurements reflect a long-term temporal scale for dietary uptake. But as tissue is constantly being replaced, and because diet may seasonally change in the wild, the exact stable-isotope turnover rate for a given tissue remains unknown (

; 

; 

). The present work aims to contribute to filling this knowledge gap by determining isotope fractionation and variability in 

J. edwardsii

.

Jasus edwardsii
is a generalist predator on rocky reefs in southeastern Australia and New Zealand (
). The size of maturity of this species varies greatly in Tasmania (
), with the current minimum legal size being 110 mm carapace length (CL) for males and 105 mm / 120 mm CL for females (in southern/northern Tasmania, respectively). Interest in the diet of this predator is currently of high importance due to their perceived potential in providing top-down predatory pressure on a range-extending pest species, the longspined sea urchin
Centrostephanus rodgersii (A. Agassiz, 1864)
(
;
). Individuals of
J. edwardsii
are used as a management strategy to control the sea urchin in Tasmania (Department of Primary Industries, Parks, Water and Environment, 2018), yet the extent to which the lobster will predate on the sea urchin is uncertain if there are more preferable prey options available (
).

Carbon and nitrogen stable isotopes were analysed consecutively for each sample using flash combustion isotope ratio mass spectrometry (varioPYRO cube coupled to Isoprime100 mass spectrometer; Elementar, Langenselbold, 
Germany
). The nitrogen produced during combustion was directly fed into the mass spectrometer and measured against a reference gas. Carbon dioxide was trapped in the meantime and released into the mass spectrometer after the nitrogen isotope measurement was completed and the system retuned accordingly. Stable isotope abundances are reported in delta (
δ
) values as the deviations from conventional standards in parts per mil (‰) from equation 1:

We calculated carbon and nitrogen discrimination factors for each diet group by subtracting the mean δ 15 N or δ 13 C value of the diet item from the mean δ 15 N or δ 13 C value of the lobsters in that treatment at 12 mo, following the equation in
. The distances between the consumer isotope signature and the relative diet-species isotope signature were averaged for the three treatments. Wild lobster isotope signatures were visualised on an isoplot along with average source signatures using no TDFs, TDFs obtained from the literature (
;
) and our experimentally derived TDFs.

We used split-plot ANOVAs to compare variability of each isotope ( δ 13 C and δ 15 N) between different tissues (dorsal muscle, leg muscle, and exoskeleton) of each lobster. Q-Qplots and Shapiro-Wilk Tests were used to visualise and confirm normality of the data. Linear regression and Pearson’s correlation were performed to determine correlation between isotopes of lobster tissues. Comparisons within tissue types across sampling periods in lobsters from different diet treatments were tested using ANOVA and post-hoc Tukey HSD tests. For lethal samples (initial, 12, and 18 mo), exoskeleton samples are the mean of leg and dorsal samples where both were collected. Exoskeleton for non-lethal samples were only leg samples. Opportunistic moult sample results were analysed separately from those from regular sampling intervals due to unequal and low numbers of replication. All data analysis was conducted using R version 4.1.1 (R
) in RStudio (
).

